            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How much turkey do I need per person?</h2>
              <p>
                Different guides give slightly different numbers, but most
                professional sources cluster around the same ranges. This
                calculator uses:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Whole turkey (on the bone)</strong>
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>No leftovers:</strong> ~1.0 lb (0.45 kg) per
                      adult, 0.5 lb (0.23 kg) per child
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Some leftovers:</strong> ~1.25 lb (0.57 kg) per
                      adult, 0.6 lb (0.27 kg) per child
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Plenty of leftovers:</strong> ~1.5 lb (0.68 kg)
                      per adult, 0.75 lb (0.34 kg) per child
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Turkey crown / breast only</strong> (less bone, more
                  meat)
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      We reduce the per-person weight by about 25% compared with
                      a whole bird.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Serving size formula</p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li><code>A</code> = number of adults</li>
                  <li><code>C</code> = number of children</li>
                  <li>
                    <code>w<sub>a</sub></code> = weight per adult (lb or kg)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <code>w<sub>c</sub></code> = weight per child (lb or kg)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the recommended turkey weight is:</p>
                <p>
                  <code>W = A × w<sub>a</sub> + C × w<sub>c</sub></code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Turkey thawing time: fridge vs. cold water</h2>
              <p>
                Safe thawing is critical. The calculator uses conservative rules
                based on widely cited food safety recommendations:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fridge thawing:</strong> about
                  <strong>24 hours per 4–5 lb</strong> (1.8–2.3 kg)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cold-water thawing:</strong> about
                  <strong>30 minutes per lb</strong> (~1 hour per kg)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>For example, a 14 lb (6.4 kg) turkey needs roughly:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> 3–4 days</li>
                <li><strong>Cold water:</strong> about 7 hours</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Fridge thawing guidelines</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Keep the turkey in its original packaging on a tray to catch
                  drips.
                </li>
                <li>Store at or below 40°F (4°C).</li>
                <li>
                  Once fully thawed, you can keep it in the fridge for 1–2 days
                  before cooking.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Cold-water thawing guidelines</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Place the turkey in a <strong>leak-proof bag</strong> to avoid
                  contamination.
                </li>
                <li>Submerge completely in <strong>cold</strong> tap water.</li>
                <li><strong>Change the water every 30 minutes.</strong></li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cook immediately</strong> after thawing; do not
                  re-refrigerate uncooked.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How long to roast a turkey</h2>
              <p>
                Roasting times vary by oven, bird shape, and whether it’s
                stuffed. This calculator uses typical averages for an unstuffed
                turkey roasted at <strong>325°F / 163°C</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Whole turkey:</strong> about
                  <strong>13–15 minutes per lb</strong> (28–33 minutes per kg)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Turkey crown / breast:</strong> slightly less, around
                  <strong>12–14 minutes per lb</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Always confirm doneness with a meat thermometer:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Insert into the
                  <strong>thickest part of the breast</strong> (not touching
                  bone).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Safe internal temperature: <strong>165°F / 74°C</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>Let the turkey rest 20–30 minutes before carving.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Brining water amount (optional)</h2>
              <p>
                If you plan to wet-brine your turkey, you need enough brine to
                fully submerge the bird. A simple planning rule is:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >About 1 quart (1 liter) of brine per 1–1.5 lb (0.5–0.7 kg)
                    of turkey.</strong
                  >
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator estimates a brine volume based on your turkey
                size so you can choose a pot or brining bag that fits.
              </p>

              <h2>Example: planning a Thanksgiving turkey</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you’re serving <strong>8 adults</strong> and
                <strong>4 children</strong>, and you want some leftovers.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Select <strong>8 adults</strong>, <strong>4 children</strong>,
                  <strong>“Some leftovers”</strong>, and
                  <strong>“Whole turkey”</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The calculator might recommend around
                  <strong>18–20 lb</strong> (8–9 kg).
                </li>
                <li>Fridge thawing time: about <strong>4–5 days</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Cold-water thawing time: about <strong>9–10 hours</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Roasting time: roughly <strong>4–4.5 hours</strong> at 325°F /
                  163°C (but always check temperature).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Safety notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Never thaw a turkey at room temperature on the counter.</li>
                <li>
                  Wash your hands and sanitize surfaces after handling raw
                  poultry.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use separate cutting boards for raw meat and ready-to-eat
                  foods.
                </li>
                <li>Refrigerate leftovers within 2 hours of cooking.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                What if I can’t find the exact turkey weight the calculator
                suggests?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Choose the <strong>next size up</strong>. It’s better to have a
                little extra meat than to run short, especially if you want
                leftovers for sandwiches or soup.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I buy fresh or frozen turkey?</h3>
              <p>
                Fresh turkeys save thawing time but usually cost more and have a
                shorter shelf life. Frozen turkeys are more flexible for
                planning but require several days to thaw safely in the fridge.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Do I need a different size if I’m serving mostly dark meat or
                white meat?
              </h3>
              <p>
                The calculator assumes a typical mix of white and dark meat. If
                your guests strongly prefer one type, you might:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Buy a slightly larger whole turkey, or</li>
                <li>Add an extra turkey breast or pack of legs/thighs.</li>
              </ul>
